[{"id":31761,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>iK</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>86</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>83</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>62</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>625</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#916;T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>984</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p>So, freezing point of solution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>273</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>984</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>269</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>016</mn><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>269</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31764,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>CRT</mi><mo>;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mo>=</mo></math> osmotic pressure<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo></math> molarity<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mo>=</mo></math> Temperature of solution let the molar mass be</p><p>Molar mass of polymer =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>42</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>bar</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>46</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>083</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8467;</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>bar</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>mol</mi><mo>.</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31710,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The boiling point elevation constant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></mfenced></math> of a volatile liquid is given by the following expression<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msubsup><mi>RT</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><msub><mi>&#916;H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msub></mfrac></math><br /><br />Where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math>boiling point of the liquid<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo></math>molar mass of the liquid<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#916;H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math> Enthalpy of vaporisation</p><p>The boiling points of the two solvents are in the ratio <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, which means that the boiling point elevation constants are also in the ratio <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>. Let&#39;s call the boiling point elevation constant of solvent <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math> as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><msub><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub></math>, and the boiling point elevation constant of solvent <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><msub><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></math>.<br />Given: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mfenced><msub><mi>&#916;H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msub></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>&#916;H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msub></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p><p>Therefore, the value of m is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn></math>(nearest integer).</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31651,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":2,"solution":"Statement I: $K_H$ is constant with respect to concentration variations in ideally dilute solutions.<br>TRUE - Henry's law constant depends only on temperature and the nature of the solute-solvent interaction. For ideally dilute solutions, $K_H$ = $P_\\text{gas}/x_\\text{solute}$ remains constant regardless of solute concentration within the dilute range.<br><br>Statement II: $K_H$ does not differ for the same solute in different solvents.<br>FALSE - Henry's law constant is solvent-dependent. The same gas or solute has different $K_H$ values in different solvents at the same temperature because the solute-solvent interactions differ. For example, CO₂ dissolves differently in water versus ethanol, giving different $K_H$ values.<br><br>Therefore, Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31724,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Let a mole <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pb</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;be added, dissociation of lead nitrate will result in:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>Pb</mi><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>&#8594;</mo></mtd><mtd><msup><mi>Pb</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo></mtd><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow></mfenced></mtd><mtd><mo>&#8658;</mo></mtd><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo></mtd><mtd><msubsup><mi>Pb</mi><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi>Cl</mi><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>PbCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable></math><br />During reformation of lead nitrate as a precipitate,<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msubsup><mi>Pb</mi><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></mtd><mtd><mo>+</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi>Cl</mi><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>PbCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8734;</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></mtd><mtd><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow></mfenced></mtd></mtr></mtable></math>&nbsp;....(i)</p><p>In final solution after addition of 0.2 moles of sodium and chloride ions:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#916;T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mn>1</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><mn>27</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>From (i),<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi>sp</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>[</mo><msup><mi>Pb</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>]</mo><mo>[</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><msup><mo>]</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><mn>27</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow><mn>27</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31846,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["The solution formed is an ideal solution","The solution is non-ideal, showing +ve deviation from Raoult's law.","The solution is non-ideal, showing -ve deviation from Raoult's law.","n-heptane shows +ve deviation while ethanol shows -ve deviation from Raoult's law."],"answer":1,"solution":"The interactions between $\\mathrm{n}$-heptane and ethanol are weaker than that in pure components.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":31738,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>We know that relative lowering in vapour pressure is given as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>0</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></msub></mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mmultiscripts><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>solute</mi></mstyle><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mmultiscripts><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi>Solute</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mmultiscripts><mi>solvent</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mmultiscripts></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>0</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></msub></mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mmultiscripts><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>solute</mi></mstyle><mprescripts/><none/><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mmultiscripts><mmultiscripts><mi>solvent</mi><mprescripts/><none/><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mmultiscripts></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>0</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mn>0</mn></msup><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mmultiscripts><mi>solute</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mmultiscripts><mmultiscripts><mi>solvent</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mmultiscripts></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>solute</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mmultiscripts><mi>solvent</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>55</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31803,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/583de7bd-aab7-46aa-a7cb-593c0004fdf1-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 240px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bac96548-221b-4bb0-a17c-e6b8379a8752-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 235px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e68c9612-365e-49b6-97d9-0cbb5ea38089-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 265px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/41d55cde-f7b5-4624-8f52-c898af7bdc10-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 239px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></msub></math></p><p>Where, <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></msub></math> is the partial pressure of gas.</p><p><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></msub></math> is&nbsp;the Henry&rsquo;s constant</p><p><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></msub></math> is&nbsp;the mole fraction of gas</p><p><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></msub></math></p><p>On comparing this with the equation of straight line,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>mx</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></math>, the intercept,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub></math>. Thus, the gas having more value of Henry&#39;s law constant will have more value of intercept on the y-axis.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31834,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["$80$","$60$","$20$","$40$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\frac{\\mathrm{P}^{\\mathrm{o}}-\\mathrm{P}_s}{\\mathrm{P}^{\\mathrm{o}}}=\\frac{n}{N}=\\frac{w}{m} \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{M}}{W}$\n$0.1=\\frac{12}{m} \\times \\frac{18}{108}$\n$m=\\frac{12 \\times 18}{0.1 \\times 108}=20$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31659,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{MX}_3 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{M}^{+3}+3 \\mathrm{X}^{\\ominus}$<br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{i}=1+(\\mathrm{n}-1) \\alpha \\\\ & \\mathrm{i}=1+(4-1) \\alpha=2\\end{aligned}$<br />$\\alpha=\\frac{1}{3}=33.33 \\% \\approx 33 \\%$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31798,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<math><mn>10</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>5</mn></math>","<math><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>0.2</mn></math>","<math><mn>5</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Elevation in Boiling point&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br /><br />For non-electrolyte,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p>m= Molar mass of solute</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>molality</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solution</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>molality</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>solution</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></msub></mrow><mrow><mo>&#8710;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31749,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Osmotic pressure&nbsp;is the minimum pressure which needs to be applied to a solution&nbsp;to prevent the inward flow of its pure solvent&nbsp;across a semipermeable membrane.It is a colligative&nbsp;property.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>CRT</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi>Where</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Osmotic</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pressure</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Molarity</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Temperature</mi><mo>.</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>CRT</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>200</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>31</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>300  &#215; 1000</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>415</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31853,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["Water - hydrochloric acid","Acetone - chloroform","Water - nitric acid","Benzene - methanol"],"answer":3,"solution":"Benzene in methanol breaks the $\\mathrm{H}$ - bonding of the alcohol making its boiling point decrease \\& there by its vapour pressure increases leading two +ve deviation.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":31665,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lkZ_VGQjj3A-HVTsfPBMETY-37JiTt7mPbWwPQexqWo.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/67dPxbgIMq53FW5gRhJ22T_qKUeSOaFpKHUNZvolVsw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/at4a0fyVoXJsbiwRYRX_n7u8NymkL8aLmkXwiQF9F2Y.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oHWg3C0JUw7uLI9XDQDuPVHw6oLkcDVefdgZJC2KKwQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\underset{1^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}}{\\text { Water }} \\xrightarrow[\\text { decreases }]{\\text { Volume }}\\underset{4^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}}{\\text { Water }} \\xrightarrow[\\text { thermal expansion }]{\\text { Volume increases }} \\underset{25^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}}{\\text { Water }}$ Water<br />$\\text { Molarity }=\\frac{\\mathrm{n}_{\\text {solute }}}{(\\text { Volume of solution })_{\\ell}}$<br />Hence<br />$1^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C} \\xrightarrow[\\text { increases }]{\\text { molarity }} 4^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C} \\xrightarrow[\\text { decreases }]{\\text { molarity }} 25^{\\circ} \\mathrm{C}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31851,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["$1+\\alpha$","$1-\\alpha$","$1+2 \\alpha$","$1-2 \\alpha$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yhQRpssL71sqaoDbtOeHiwLzsiFJhrpC0iZsiOdwm98.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nTotal moles $=1+2 \\alpha$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":31667,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/q2drfpU3z_N-JUbwRVd0ADbcxU-rzhK6sH1dWKBUC1o.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xWPC16x1Ra6Zl2R0J_nGtoMV0t66k_0p_Uyz_UfsnMQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kUciU6QtKKcQh8Ham0CAIzYfaS5touDIWNRjqTWuu8o.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/33SUxoFwTGkkIsAv9illxhS7qc4qLWSNu3jGZOgq8hc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"As temperature increases solubility first decrease then increase hence \\(\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{H}}\\) first increase than decrease also at moderate temperature \\(\\mathrm{K}_{\\mathrm{H}}\\) value \\(\\mathrm{He}  \\gt  \\mathrm{N}_2  \\gt  \\mathrm{CH}_4\\).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31677,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["(i)  &lt; (ii) &lt; (iii) &lt; (iv)","(iv)  &lt; (iii) &lt; (i) &lt; (ii)","(ii)  &lt; (i$) \\equiv($iii) &lt; (iv)","(ii)  &lt; (i) &lt; (iii) &lt; (iv)"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\Delta \\mathrm{T}_{\\mathrm{b}}=\\mathrm{i} \\mathrm{~K}_{\\mathrm{b}} . \\mathrm{m} . \\propto \\mathrm{i} . \\mathrm{C} .$\nwhere $\\mathrm{C}=$ concentration\n$\\begin{array}{|l|c|}\n\\hline \\text { Options } & \\text { i.C. } \\\\\n\\hline \\text { (i) } & 2 \\times 10^{-4} \\\\\n\\hline \\text { (ii) } & 1 \\times 10^{-4} \\\\\n\\hline \\text { (iii) } & 2 \\times 10^{-3} \\\\\n\\hline \\text { (iv) } & 2 \\times 10^{-2} \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}$\n\n\n\nB.P. order :\n$\\text { (ii) } < \\text { (i) } < \\text { (iii) } < \\text { (iv) }$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31701,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["increased vapour pressure, increased boiling point","increased vapour pressure, decreased boiling point","decreased vapour pressure, decreased boiling point","decreased vapour pressure, increased boiling point"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Raoult's law states that a solvent's partial vapour pressure in a solution (or mixture) is equal or identical to the vapour pressure of the pure solvent multiplied by its mole fraction in the solution.</p><p>The compounds which show negative deviation from Raoult's law are a mixture of acetone and chloroform. This results in the formation of the hydrogen bonding between atoms of molecules. There is a decrease in the vapour pressure of the mixture that results in a negative deviation from Raoult's law.</p><p>Solution with negative deviation has<br/><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo> </mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mn>0</mn></msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo> </mo><mo>+</mo><mo> </mo><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mn>0</mn></msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mn>0</mn></msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><mo> </mo><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mn>0</mn></msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub></math><br/> If vapour pressure decreases, so the boiling point increases.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31675,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}, \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_2^0-\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}, \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_2^0-\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}, \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0-\\mathrm{P}_2^0}{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}$","$\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}, \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0-\\mathrm{P}_2^0}{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Given mole fraction of liquid 1 in liquid and vapour phase is $x_1$ and $y_1$ respectively.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZYP2Z_DjqkV7FiPFkgzqA4OCvPDI1s6oCdNvcRnoAms.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{P}_1=\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{T}} y_1=\\mathrm{P}_1^0 x_1 \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_{\\mathrm{T}}}{x_1}=\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{y_1} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_2^0+x_1\\left(\\mathrm{P}_1^0+\\mathrm{P}_2^0\\right)}{x_1}=\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{y_1} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}{x_1}+\\left(\\mathrm{P}_1^0+\\mathrm{P}_2^0\\right)=\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{y_1} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}{x_1}=\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{y_1}-\\left(\\mathrm{P}_1^0+\\mathrm{P}_2^0\\right) \\\\ & \\frac{1}{x_1}=\\frac{1}{y_2}\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1^0}{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}\\right)-\\frac{\\left(\\mathrm{P}_1^0+\\mathrm{P}_2^0\\right)}{\\mathrm{P}_2^0}\\end{aligned}$\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{1}{x_1}=\\frac{1}{y_2}\\left(\\frac{P_1^0}{P_2^0}\\right)+\\frac{\\left(P_2^0-P_1^0\\right)}{P_2^0} \\\\ & y=m x+c \\\\ & \\text { Slope }=\\frac{P_1^0}{P_2^0} ; \\text { Intercept }=\\frac{P_2^0-P_1^0}{P_2^0}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31723,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A-III, B-I, C-II, D-IV","A-III, B-II, C-I, D-IV","A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II","A-I, B-III, C-II, D-IV"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>(A) van&#39;t Hoff factor, it is used in measuring colligative properties</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mtext>&#160;Normal molar mass&#160;</mtext><mtext>&#160;Abnormal molar mass&#160;</mtext></mfrac></math></p><p>(B) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math> Cryoscopic constant or molal freezing constant</p><p>(C) Solutions with same osmotic pressure are known as isotonic solutions.</p><p>(D) Solutions with same composition of vapour over them are called Azeotrope or azeotrophic mixtures.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31691,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub></math>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></math></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>It is because the extent or degree of dissociation increases with increase in dilution of a solution. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>001</mn><mo> </mo><mi>M</mi><mo> </mo><mi>N</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi></math> solution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>'</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>'</mo></math> is most diluted as compared to the other two <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>C</mi><mi>l</mi></math> solutions. The vant Hoff factor (i) depends on extent of dilution.This confirms answer at (i) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>&lt;</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8d479075-3b31-47c9-bc2f-e257584d26a5.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 96px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31840,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["$\\alpha=\\frac{i-1}{x+y+1}$","$\\alpha=\\frac{x+y-1}{i-1}$","$\\alpha=\\frac{x+y+1}{i-1}$","$\\alpha=\\frac{i-1}{(x+y-1)}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& i=1-\\alpha+n \\alpha=1+\\alpha(n-1) \\\\\n& \\frac{i-1}{n-1}=\\alpha \\\\\n& A_x B_y \\rightarrow x A^{+y}+y B^{-x} \\\\\n& n=x+y\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nSo $\\alpha=\\frac{i-1}{x+y-1}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":31757,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["glycine","hydrazine","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KHSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","glucose"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#916;T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ik</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br />As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math> is same for all electrolyte so<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#916;T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math><br />Greater the value of i greater is depression in freezing point<br />For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KHSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math><br />And for Glucose, Ethylele Glycol &amp; glycerol <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31765,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#916;T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>molality</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Molar</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>250</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31807,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["1.6","1.8","20","22"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{K}_{2} \\mathrm{Hgl}_{4} \\rightleftharpoons 2 \\mathrm{~K}^{+}+\\left[\\mathrm{Hgl}_{4}\\right]^{2-} ; \\mathrm{n}=3$\r\n\r\n$$\r\n\r\n\\begin{aligned}\r\n\r\n\\because & \\alpha=\\frac{i-1}{n-1} ; 0.4=\\frac{\\mathrm{i}-1}{3-1} \\\\\r\n\r\n& i=1.8\r\n\r\n\\end{aligned}\r\n\r\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31769,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mmHg</mi><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>25</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mo>&#8728;</mo></mmultiscripts><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mmHg</mi></math></p><p>and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"\" close=\"}\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mm</mi></math></p><p>Now mol fraction of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> in the vapour phase</p><p>i.e.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></msub><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msubsup></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>therefore:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31852,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["Same boiling point but different freezing point","Same freezing point but different boiling point","Same boiling and same freezing points","Different boiling and different freezing points"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":31754,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>&#160;Mole of&#160;</mtext><msub><mi>CuSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mn>5</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>80</mn><mrow><mn>249</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>32</mn></math></p><p>Concentration of the copper sulphate solution&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mtext>&#160;mole&#160;</mtext><mrow><mtext>&#160;volume&#160;</mtext><mo>(</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>32</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>064</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31854,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["Liquid oxygen $+$ liquid argon","Liquid hydrogen + liquid oxygen","Liquid nitrogen $+$ liquid oxygen","Liquid hydrogen $+$ liquid nitrogen"],"answer":1,"solution":"Liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen are used as excellent fuel for rockets. $\\mathrm{H}_2(l)$ has low mass and high enthalpy of combustion whereas oxygen is a strong supporter of combustion","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":31715,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solutions","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dd736056-1851-4c3a-97a3-9dc635abdeca-9896632.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 138px;\" /></p><p>At equivalence point,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math>mmole of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi><mo>=</mo></math> mmole of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mmole</mi></math></p><p>Volume of solution <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mi>ml</mi></math></p><p>Mass of solution<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#961;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mL</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p>Formula unit mass of potassium chloride =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>39</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>gmol</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>74</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>gmol</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Thus, Mass of solvent</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>-</mo></math>&nbsp;mass of&nbsp;solute</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>-</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>74</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>23</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>51</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p>Thus, molality of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>&#160;mole of&#160;</mtext><mi>KCl</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>&#160;mass of solvent in&#160;</mtext><mi>kg</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>23</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>51</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>85</mn></math></p><p>i of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>(</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>%</mo></math> ionisation )</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><msub><mi>&#916;T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>85</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;K</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null}]